<HEAD>List of Deadliest U.S. Quakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With SF Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tuesday's earthquake in the San Francisco Bay area apparently
was the second-deadliest in U.S. history. Here is a list of major
quakes as recorded by the U. S. Geological Survey:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SAN FRANCISCO, APRIL 18-19, 1906</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Rated at 8.3 on the Richter scale. Ruptured gas lines,
overturned stoves and started fires that destroyed much of the city
and claimed hundreds of lives. Traditional estimates put the death
toll at 500 to 700, but the city archivist recently established
that at least 2,500, and possibly 5,000 people were killed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, OCT. 17, 1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Registered 6.9 on the Richter scale. Collapsed a mile-long
stretch of double-deck highway, inflicted widespread damage to
buildings. Struck at evening rush hour. More than 200 people killed
and 400 injured, according to early official reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PRINCE WILLIAM SOUND, ALASKA, MARCH 27, 1964</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richter reading 8.4. The infamous Good Friday Earthquake. There
were 131 deaths and extensive damage in Alaska.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MONA PASSAGE, PUERTO RICO, OCT. 11, 1918</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Rated at 7.5 on the Richter scale. Shook the Mona Passage
between Puerto Rico and the island of Hispaniola. Some 116 people
died, many in the giant wave generated by the quake.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LONG BEACH, CALIF., MARCH 10, 1933</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Rated at 6.2 on the Richter scale. Hit a heavily populated area.
Many buildings collapsed, including schools, and 115 people were
killed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SAN FERNANDO VALLEY, CALIF., FEB. 9, 1971</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richter reading 6.4. Killed 65 people.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHARLESTON, S.C., AUG. 31, 1886</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Rated at 6.6 on the Richter scale. Killed 60 people. Was felt as
far away as Boston, Milwaukee and Havana, Cuba.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HEBGEN LAKE, MONT., AUG. 17, 1959</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richter reading 7.3. Was felt from Seattle to North Dakota to
Utah. Extensive damage was reported and 28 people died.
</TEXT>
